00:48:15.690 --> 00:48:19.210
Political cartoonists
for example,

00:48:19.210 --> 00:48:22.400
a lot of them still do drawing,

00:48:22.400 --> 00:48:28.450
add color digitally,
abandon that.

00:48:28.450 --> 00:48:30.230
We have a couple of editorial--

00:48:30.230 --> 00:48:36.770
a political cartoonist in the
audience here and so, yeah,

00:48:36.770 --> 00:48:38.070
there's a lot still to do.

00:48:38.070 --> 00:48:39.370
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki:
Even right now,

00:48:39.370 --> 00:48:41.460
especially like illustrate--
because like the weight of--

00:48:41.460 --> 00:48:43.860
it's easier to make a book, it's
easier to make a printed T-shirt

00:48:43.860 --> 00:48:45.160
or make a button or whatever.

00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:49.690
Like all this stuff is just--
it's this whole different way

00:48:49.690 --> 00:48:50.990
of being an illustrator now

00:48:50.990 --> 00:48:54.130
and like selling your stuff
directly online and so it--

00:48:54.130 --> 00:48:57.380
do you have then collect
objects, you know, of all these

00:48:57.380 --> 00:49:00.140
like screen for the tote
bags like maybe, maybe that's

00:49:00.140 --> 00:49:03.650
like this big part
of illustration now.

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:04.950
&gt;&gt; Martha Kennedy: Yeah.

00:49:04.950 --> 00:49:06.250
And on the other hand
though it is nice

00:49:06.250 --> 00:49:10.280
to have high quality
prints, archival prints so,

00:49:10.280 --> 00:49:14.650
they give you a sense of
the sampling of a, you know,

00:49:14.650 --> 00:49:19.260
up and coming or award winning
illustrator now, you know.

00:49:19.260 --> 00:49:21.260
Other questions?

00:49:21.260 --> 00:49:22.980
Yeah.

00:49:22.980 --> 00:49:25.350
&gt;&gt; This question is for Barbara.

00:49:25.350 --> 00:49:28.920
Barbara, I really
enjoyed your strip

00:49:28.920 --> 00:49:31.900
when it was being syndicated
and I just wander could you talk

00:49:31.900 --> 00:49:34.900
about why you gave it up?

00:49:34.900 --> 00:49:37.780
&gt;&gt; Barbara Brandon-Croft:
Because I stopped being paid.

00:49:37.780 --> 00:49:45.450
Basically, with newspaper comic
strip, the way it works is you--

00:49:45.450 --> 00:49:47.240
the newspapers pay the syndicate

00:49:47.240 --> 00:49:49.830
and the syndicate gives you
a portion of what gets paid,

00:49:49.830 --> 00:49:52.250
so you can-- You'll have a
contract with a syndicate

00:49:52.250 --> 00:49:56.030
that will say, if you go below
a certain number of papers,

00:49:56.030 --> 00:50:01.450
you have-- You can say I'm
done or we can say we're done.

00:50:01.450 --> 00:50:06.090
And to Universal Press' credit,
they kept me on a long time

00:50:06.090 --> 00:50:07.730
when they could have dropped me.

00:50:07.730 --> 00:50:11.680
I think they felt a
certain kind of, you know,

00:50:11.680 --> 00:50:13.000
they needed me [laughter].

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:15.480
I mean, you know, so they can
say we have the black woman,

00:50:15.480 --> 00:50:17.840
you know, and that's really
good because they really needed

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:20.510
to be able to say that and so--

00:50:20.510 --> 00:50:23.790
But as newspapers
started declining--

00:50:23.790 --> 00:50:28.550
And when I first started in, you
know, the early '90s, you know,

00:50:28.550 --> 00:50:32.790
'90, they-- Universal
Press sent out a letter

00:50:32.790 --> 00:50:35.800
to all their creators
and said, you know,

00:50:35.800 --> 00:50:38.330
newspapers are on the decline.

00:50:38.330 --> 00:50:41.780
And so not only-- it's
the same strip that goes

00:50:41.780 --> 00:50:44.600
out to every newspaper but
if the circulation is larger

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:46.530
for newspaper, you
get paid more.

00:50:46.530 --> 00:50:52.230
So when circulations go down and
newspapers start dropping off,

00:50:52.230 --> 00:50:55.030
then paychecks gets smaller
and then they think, oh,

00:50:55.030 --> 00:50:57.570
it's not worth it,
you know, all the work

00:50:57.570 --> 00:51:00.160
and energy to keep just.

00:51:00.160 --> 00:51:03.270
So, it was a certain time
when I was doing the strip

00:51:03.270 --> 00:51:06.240
that I started also
doing other gigs.

00:51:06.240 --> 00:51:07.990
You know, it's like I've
got to do some other things

00:51:07.990 --> 00:51:12.690
to keep my life going so I, you
know, worked in other areas.

00:51:12.690 --> 00:51:14.150
&gt;&gt; What did you do?

00:51:14.150 --> 00:51:15.450
&gt;&gt; Barbara Brandon-Croft:
Many things [laughter].

00:51:15.450 --> 00:51:17.240
But what I did, it
seems like I stayed

00:51:17.240 --> 00:51:20.150
in publishing for a lot of it.

00:51:20.150 --> 00:51:22.680
But I also did fashion
stuff and--

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:25.490
but like I've been
at Parents Magazine

00:51:25.490 --> 00:51:27.430
for a hundred years now.

00:51:27.430 --> 00:51:31.170
I mean, that was-- I see
somebody I used to work

00:51:31.170 --> 00:51:33.530
with [laughs] but--
and that for so long--

00:51:33.530 --> 00:51:36.560
and I'm the research director
there, but how did that happen?

00:51:36.560 --> 00:51:38.880
You-- well, you're a-- And they
don't know I'm a cartoonist.

00:51:38.880 --> 00:51:40.480
They're like, oh, you have
such nice handwriting.

00:51:40.480 --> 00:51:44.110
I was like, thank you [laughs].

00:51:44.110 --> 00:51:48.440
Thanks. So that's how it goes.

00:51:48.440 --> 00:51:49.770
&gt;&gt; OK.

00:51:49.770 --> 00:51:51.720
&gt;&gt; Barbara Brandon-Croft: Yeah.

00:51:51.720 --> 00:51:53.020
&gt;&gt; Martha Kennedy: OK.

00:51:53.020 --> 00:51:54.320
Another question.

00:51:54.320 --> 00:51:55.620
&gt;&gt; Denise Lauder: Hi.

00:51:55.620 --> 00:51:58.040
I am Denise Lauder [assumed
spelling], longtime friend

00:51:58.040 --> 00:52:03.540
of Barbara's but I've
wanted to ask all of you

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:06.760
if today's climate especially--

00:52:06.760 --> 00:52:09.480
well, we'll start with
the younger generation

00:52:09.480 --> 00:52:10.780
here [laughs].

00:52:10.780 --> 00:52:12.890
But someone who is
using the online medium

00:52:12.890 --> 00:52:15.930
and I really think you
could go back, Barbara,

00:52:15.930 --> 00:52:17.800
and do what you do online.

00:52:17.800 --> 00:52:21.150
They're business models
for something like that.

00:52:21.150 --> 00:52:23.370
My son is making money
and I don't know what

00:52:23.370 --> 00:52:26.900
in the heck is [inaudible]
[laughter].

00:52:26.900 --> 00:52:29.470
I'm off topic.

00:52:29.470 --> 00:52:34.320
Does today's climate, you know,
politics and the vitriol that's

00:52:34.320 --> 00:52:38.800
on the internet affect
or impact--

00:52:38.800 --> 00:52:41.770
you know, what is on the
internet or not affect

00:52:41.770 --> 00:52:45.540
or impact the work that
you and the words--

00:52:45.540 --> 00:52:48.570
the pictures that you want to
draw and what you want to say,

00:52:48.570 --> 00:52:52.550
does it diminish it or
does it fire you up?

00:52:52.550 --> 00:52:54.720
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki: I think
that that it totally has

00:52:54.720 --> 00:52:57.070
and I think that there is this--

00:52:57.070 --> 00:52:59.560
&gt;&gt; Barbara Brandon-Croft:
Fired you up?

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:02.240
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki: Well, I think
that it has impacted for sure.

00:53:02.240 --> 00:53:04.140
Like I think that
now illustrators--

00:53:04.140 --> 00:53:07.330
especially because you're
responding in real time

00:53:07.330 --> 00:53:09.230
and it feels like
almost distorted

00:53:09.230 --> 00:53:12.400
to then post a nice
picture of a flower

00:53:12.400 --> 00:53:15.180
when a school shooting
has happened, right.

00:53:15.180 --> 00:53:16.720
So like I think that there--

00:53:16.720 --> 00:53:19.260
because illustrators and
cartoonists are so much

00:53:19.260 --> 00:53:22.330
in dialog with our audience,
it's very intimate relationship.

00:53:22.330 --> 00:53:26.450
Like in a weird way you're
like you're kind of--

00:53:26.450 --> 00:53:28.340
it can be tough because you
end up being like if you feel

00:53:28.340 --> 00:53:30.700
like you're entertaining for
free or you're like some sort

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:35.630
of like online buddy to like
30,000 people or whatever.

00:53:35.630 --> 00:53:39.510
And so I think-- and I
think that now because a lot

00:53:39.510 --> 00:53:42.060
of the people that
really infuses new energy

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:44.150
into illustration are
younger and more political

00:53:44.150 --> 00:53:46.610
and more diverse, I
think there is a demand

00:53:46.610 --> 00:53:50.550
to question and comment.

00:53:50.550 --> 00:53:56.080
And it doesn't exist
in a vacuum.

00:53:56.080 --> 00:53:58.050
I think that that increasingly--

00:53:58.050 --> 00:54:00.230
it feels very out of
touch if somebody thinks

00:54:00.230 --> 00:54:02.580
like their work is not
connected to the world

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:05.670
and it doesn't respond to
the world, then I think some

00:54:05.670 --> 00:54:09.020
of that is the current
fashion of thinking as well

00:54:09.020 --> 00:54:13.690
but I don't-- I kind of
agree, you know what I mean?

00:54:13.690 --> 00:54:17.850
It doesn't exist in a vacuum and
if you don't respond that means

00:54:17.850 --> 00:54:20.950
that you're privileged enough
to not have to respond, so yeah.

00:54:20.950 --> 00:54:22.640
&gt;&gt; Martha Kennedy: Or
maybe you just want

00:54:22.640 --> 00:54:24.520
to be a little more thoughtful--

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:25.820
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki: Yeah.

00:54:25.820 --> 00:54:27.120
&gt;&gt; Martha Kennedy: --
before you respond.

00:54:27.120 --> 00:54:28.420
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki: Yeah.

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:29.720
&gt;&gt; Barbara Brandon-Croft:
That will be novel.

00:54:29.720 --> 00:54:31.020
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki:
Yeah [laughter].

00:54:31.020 --> 00:54:32.320
&gt;&gt; Barbara Brandon-Croft:
The whole world.

00:54:32.320 --> 00:54:33.620
&gt;&gt; We have time for
one more question.

00:54:33.620 --> 00:54:34.920
We've got a gentleman here.

00:54:34.920 --> 00:54:36.220
&gt;&gt; Sorry. Hi.

00:54:36.220 --> 00:54:37.520
So there's some really
great hashtags trending

00:54:37.520 --> 00:54:40.380
on Twitter right now for women
in illustration and kidlit women

00:54:40.380 --> 00:54:44.930
and part of that is also a big
conversation about, you know,

00:54:44.930 --> 00:54:48.570
the kidlit industry is--
there's a lot of women working

00:54:48.570 --> 00:54:50.660
in that industry, right,
and even in that very,

00:54:50.660 --> 00:54:53.970
very high levels but there are
still some inequality in terms

00:54:53.970 --> 00:54:56.000
of the awards, especially
in the illustration side.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:58.060
I'm just wondering if you
have any particular thoughts

00:54:58.060 --> 00:55:00.650
about that conversation and
just to make sure people know

00:55:00.650 --> 00:55:01.990
about these hashtags
because there's a lot

00:55:01.990 --> 00:55:04.980
of great stuff being promoted.

00:55:04.980 --> 00:55:09.020
Kidlit women and
women in illustration.

00:55:09.020 --> 00:55:10.320
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki: Yeah.

00:55:10.320 --> 00:55:12.730
I mean-- well, I have a
new picture book out so I'm

00:55:12.730 --> 00:55:14.320
like sort of thinking
about this and running

00:55:14.320 --> 00:55:15.840
in that circle a lot right now.

00:55:15.840 --> 00:55:18.420
And it's again, like I sort
of said at the beginning,

00:55:18.420 --> 00:55:23.810
it's fascinating because it's
a matriarchy in some ways.

00:55:23.810 --> 00:55:25.560
But some of those
persistent problems,

00:55:25.560 --> 00:55:29.060
it's just when powers starts
like coming into it for example.

00:55:29.060 --> 00:55:34.290
I am super interested to know
that, you know, a lot of young,

00:55:34.290 --> 00:55:39.380
hot, attractive men
get these are perceived

00:55:39.380 --> 00:55:40.990
to get ahead in this way.

00:55:40.990 --> 00:55:42.630
And you're just like
that's so disappointing

00:55:42.630 --> 00:55:47.380
that that is just a flip of
like this power thing [laughs].

00:55:47.380 --> 00:55:53.290
But it's-- again, a lot of it
is tied into any other industry

00:55:53.290 --> 00:55:55.440
like what-- like of me too.

00:55:55.440 --> 00:55:58.120
You know, it's like kids that's
having this me too moment

00:55:58.120 --> 00:56:00.270
and people are somehow shocked.

00:56:00.270 --> 00:56:02.220
But it's an industry,
it's money, it's power,

00:56:02.220 --> 00:56:05.970
it's influence, it's
fame, all these things.

00:56:05.970 --> 00:56:08.720
And once you've put that into
the mix, it's like all the--

00:56:08.720 --> 00:56:10.590
Those patterns just recur.

00:56:10.590 --> 00:56:18.700
But I don't know, it's-- I think
that sometimes this is a very

00:56:18.700 --> 00:56:20.110
like nebulous industry.

00:56:20.110 --> 00:56:24.570
It's like how do
you become popular?

00:56:24.570 --> 00:56:28.150
How do you get a book deal?

00:56:28.150 --> 00:56:30.370
How do you become
book to do speaking?

00:56:30.370 --> 00:56:31.970
How do you-- Where
do you get invited?

00:56:31.970 --> 00:56:33.270
All these becomes just like--

00:56:33.270 --> 00:56:35.780
and it's like there's
a lot of socializing

00:56:35.780 --> 00:56:37.080
and there's a lot of, you know--

00:56:37.080 --> 00:56:39.780
that's how the industry of
publishing kind of works

00:56:39.780 --> 00:56:44.440
and that can favor certain
types of people and then

00:56:44.440 --> 00:56:46.840
and it all gets like
kind of gray zoned.

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:49.520
There's a lot gray zone
in a lot of publishing.

00:56:49.520 --> 00:56:50.820
Maybe that's all industry

00:56:50.820 --> 00:56:53.680
but that gray zone can be really
frustrating because you have

00:56:53.680 --> 00:56:58.310
to be able to navigate
it, to thrive and then

00:56:58.310 --> 00:57:01.750
but also to stay sane, so.

00:57:01.750 --> 00:57:05.300
&gt;&gt; Whitney Sherman: I was going
to say hashtags are great.

00:57:05.300 --> 00:57:09.820
It's a great way to find stuff
if you're looking on the web

00:57:09.820 --> 00:57:15.680
or on social media but
in a way it's endemic

00:57:15.680 --> 00:57:18.650
of where we are right
now, politically.

00:57:18.650 --> 00:57:23.500
It's this burgeoning industry
of recognizing women in a way,

00:57:23.500 --> 00:57:25.120
if you know what I mean.

00:57:25.120 --> 00:57:29.430
It's like a thing to do and
I hope that we get past that,

00:57:29.430 --> 00:57:32.220
that we survive this trend.

00:57:32.220 --> 00:57:33.920
I don't want to be a trend.

00:57:33.920 --> 00:57:36.520
I want to be just
part of the whole.

00:57:36.520 --> 00:57:40.200
And so the hashtagging
is great if you want

00:57:40.200 --> 00:57:43.300
to sense the community, right,

00:57:43.300 --> 00:57:46.220
as you can see how many
other people are using

00:57:46.220 --> 00:57:47.660
that same hashtag.

00:57:47.660 --> 00:57:52.500
It's a way to connect in with
certain very specific topics,

00:57:52.500 --> 00:57:54.730
whether it's children's
literature

00:57:54.730 --> 00:57:57.080
or generally women
in illustration.

00:57:57.080 --> 00:57:59.110
They're kind of two
different things.

00:57:59.110 --> 00:58:05.410
But I just have this
great hope for a future

00:58:05.410 --> 00:58:10.500
that doesn't need a hashtag
like that for it to be vital.

00:58:10.500 --> 00:58:11.970
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki: Well,
I think the kidlit women

00:58:11.970 --> 00:58:14.820
in particular is
a response to some

00:58:14.820 --> 00:58:20.800
of that recent me too
stuff, #metoo stuff.

00:58:20.800 --> 00:58:23.610
I do think it also deserve
as like an educational tool

00:58:23.610 --> 00:58:26.700
for people that are starting
and they don't know the way

00:58:26.700 --> 00:58:28.440
that it works and
now they're quickly--

00:58:28.440 --> 00:58:32.780
so maybe that's good and that
it helps people prevent falling

00:58:32.780 --> 00:58:37.320
into these traps or these bad
situations before their career

00:58:37.320 --> 00:58:39.760
is at that point,
so I don't know.

00:58:39.760 --> 00:58:41.060
&gt;&gt; Martha Kennedy: Yeah.

00:58:41.060 --> 00:58:42.360
No. That's terrific.

00:58:42.360 --> 00:58:43.660
I mean over a hundred--

00:58:43.660 --> 00:58:46.500
This sort of is a good ending
point I think perhaps [laughs].

00:58:46.500 --> 00:58:48.010
&gt;&gt; Jillian Tamaki:
Hashtag learning.

00:58:48.010 --> 00:58:51.550
&gt;&gt; Martha Kennedy: From
hashtags to, you know,

00:58:51.550 --> 00:58:55.920
over a hundred years ago,
Cecilia Beaux dreamed of a time

00:58:55.920 --> 00:59:00.440
when the notion of women
and art would become strange

00:59:00.440 --> 00:59:06.960
as mentioning men in art,
so we're moving toward that.

00:59:06.960 --> 00:59:08.840
&gt;&gt; Helena Zinkham: So how
